narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I acquired a basic familiarity with the resources available to scholars of classical antiquity here at Yale as well as trends in some of the discipline's major subfields.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Often, this course felt more like busy-work than effective educational engagement. Some of the assignments were fun, but the variation in instruction style, assignment, and reading work from week-to-week was difficult to manage at times.

This course went as well as any proseminar could go; that is to say, it went quite well and fulfilled the goals it set out to accomplish. Something that might be addressed is the schedule of readings and assignments. Some of these were left quite obscure on the final syllabus. In the future it would help for planning purposes to provide a full list of readings and assignments to supplement the occasionally cryptic outline on the syllabus.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: The course is required, so no choice for Classics PhD students.
